## 6. Notification Integration

### Notification Changes

The `notifications` table gets a new nullable column `reaction_type` (text).

When a reaction is created:
```javascript
// In reactionService.js
await supabase.from('notifications').insert({
    sender_id: senderId,
    receiver_id: receiverId,
    journal_id: journalId,
    type: 'reaction',
    reaction_type: reactionType,  // 'fire', 'heart', etc.
    read: false
});
```

When a reaction is removed, delete the corresponding notification:
```javascript
await supabase.from('notifications')
    .delete()
    .eq('sender_id', senderId)
    .eq('receiver_id', receiverId)
    .eq('journal_id', journalId)
    .eq('type', 'reaction');
```

When a reaction type is switched, update the existing notification:
```javascript
await supabase.from('notifications')
    .update({ reaction_type: newReactionType })
    .eq('sender_id', senderId)
    .eq('receiver_id', receiverId)
    .eq('journal_id', journalId)
    .eq('type', 'reaction');
```

### Notification Display Updates

In `notificationsCards.jsx`, add to the `iconArray`:
```javascript
{
    type: 'reaction',
    icon: null,  // Dynamic -- handled separately using reaction_type
}
```

For the reaction notification icon, instead of a static SVG, render the emoji itself from `REACTION_MAP[notification.reaction_type]?.emoji`. This makes "Sarah reacted [fire emoji] to your post" immediately visible.

In `formatNoficationType.js`:
```javascript
reaction: 'Reacted to your post'
```

The notification rendering section would need a small conditional:
```jsx
{displayType === 'reaction' && notification.reaction_type && (
    <span className="notif-reaction-emoji">
        {REACTION_MAP[notification.reaction_type]?.emoji}
    </span>
)}
```

